  "prompt": "How does netflix achieve the logo animation upon leaving netflix.com?",
  "response": "Netflix's logo animation when leaving the site involves a combination of web technologies including HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Here is a high-level overview of how such an effect might be implemented:\n\n1. **HTML Structure**: Ensuring there is an element to attach the animation to, such as a div with the Netflix logo.\n\n2. **CSS Styling**: Using CSS to define the initial and final states of the animation. This could involve keyframe animations and transitions.\n\n```css\n@keyframes logoAnimation {\n  0% {\n    opacity: 1;\n    transform: scale(1);\n  }\n  100% {\n    opacity: 0;\n    transform: scale(2);\n  }\n}\n\n.logo {\n  animation-name: logoAnimation;\n  animation-duration: 1s;\n  animation-fill-mode: forwards;\n}\n```\n\n3. **JavaScript/Animation Libraries**: Employing JavaScript or an animation library such as GSAP (GreenSock Animation Platform) to control the timing and execution of the animation when the user decides to leave the site.\n\n```javascript\nwindow.addEventListener('beforeunload', (event) => {\n  const logo = document.querySelector('.logo');\n  logo.classList.add('animations');\n  \n  // The following line prevents the logo animation interruption \n  event.returnValue = '';\n});\n```\n\n4. **Event Listeners**: Creating an event listener for navigation actions.\n\n```javascript\nwindow.addEventListener('beforeunload', function (event) {\n    // Ensure logo animation is triggered before unload\n    var logo = document.querySelector('.logo');\n    logo.style.animationPlayState = 'running';\n});\n```\n\nThis code is a simplified version, and actual implementation might vary depending on Netflix's specific requirements and optimization practices. They may also use more complex and proprietary methods to achieve a seamless and polished user experience.\n\nTo see the exact implementation, you would need to analyze the web source using developer tools in your browser while observing how the logo behaves during various interactions.",
